Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the release of the Minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes at second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison by the alleged signing of a disadvantageous Russian agreement for Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not yet firm, the Court of Appeal has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West there had been doubts about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code against which the former Prime Minister was sentenced was supported by 147 members of the vote.
226 votes were required for approval.
