History of IBM: from cheese cutter to space flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was already adopted in 1924 - originally a brand used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The basis for the birth of IBM arises from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
It had inventions such as the famous "watch to watch", which allows to control the entry and exit of the employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired his supervisory council until 1930.
Flint appointed the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM ( Watson's ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are supported).
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business equipment, from meat cutters and cheese to register boxes.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, billing doubled to $9 million and began the great expansion of the company across the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, almost 40 years later, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM personnel and computers helped NASA to guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classics "pecés", which established the computer standard of that time, arrived at the market with the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer full advice and high value added services.
The strategy that has paid IBM over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, "a smarter planet".
Its objective is to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not been improved, for example, with regard to transport and city administration.
For the trade sector, IBM presented not long ago the "Smart Commerce" platform that allows retailers to manage the full business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 he opened a branch in the then Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates the strategic centre for outsourcing in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Here too, there is a world-famous research team working with voice recognition.
