How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold travel only to the socialist bloc in most cases, as travels to the West were very restricted.
The Czech tourists therefore went on vacation to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually not even by the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies offered trips to the West in those days, but one had to line up with a sleeping bag and spend all night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still, it wasn't all won.
The so-called "change promise" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable person", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of change, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of summer cottages and houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way of traveling from the Czechs has had a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was not going to be the holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria anymore, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the current favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989, could not be travelled freely, because it was part of the Yugoslavia of that time.
In the early 1990s, visa exemption was imposed to travel to neighbouring Western European States, causing a huge wave of short-term visits, particularly to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, didn't see any maps of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech groups were sleeping in the parks in the tents, as our income from that time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs at that time was taking with them the food (conservations, stuffed, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of Czech crown convertibility, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy free Western currency.
Our standard of living increased, and with it also average wages, which about 1997 resulted in an increase in travel demand.
With increased travel demand the agencies began, from 1997 onwards regularly, to prepare trips using charter flights connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts by the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90th century, the Czechs were already travelling without visa to almost all the developed countries, except the United States, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have been leaving each year, making countries distant and warm. This winter will be flying directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States eliminated visas for Czech tourists, so our country became among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head abroad, including expenses on the site of stay.
