Walls have eyes: How researchers are studying you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another type that aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having carried out a massacre in Norway in July, which left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time before his attack against his computer, talking to some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing social media groups.
After the tragedy this summer, the researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just have to go on Facebook.
"We realized that it wasn't so hard to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report on European digital populism by the UK DEMOS study centre.
Facebook's personal information alloy is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific precision - the way sellers have been using for years.
The Bartlett team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then sent them ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes to violence and optimism about their own future.
Upon arriving through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 extreme right matches in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a totally new way of doing an investigation," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry at immigration.
However, in a sort of twist, "those who combine their activism in line with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen."
DEMOS's work is just an example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in the "I like", messages on the walls and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating an increase in research, boosting the number of academic jobs with the name of the site in the title up to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study the people you couldn't get close to with a folder on the street.
"In the past, when you were trying to poll people in the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You should go through the party, and they would never allow you access," Bartlett says.
"Facebook eliminates all that -- you're going to them directly."
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study conducted by Dr. Megan Moreno, University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues, found that university students who talked about their drunken exploits on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential advisers, could control the site and intervene to help a student who publishes too many state updates with their drunkards.
"You can't handle a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Child Health, Behavior and Development Center at Seattle's Child Research Institute, Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "punching" its own population to obtain data.
The Site Data Team has developed statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - digital freedom defenders long ago who claim that the site should make available to others its large amount of research data).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice to be able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey that they don't even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
"I don't think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining his profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study that carried out with the public Facebook walls of students.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that an investigation topic is being completely honest.
