Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for personal as well as professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the past six decades in prestigious universities that carried out deep research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about the lie have been rebutted.
Liars do look in the eyes.
They don't always stutter, whisper, rub or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and times.
I spent several years investigating scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and help to navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include recruitment, interviews, or negotiation management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to make others feel at ease, handling their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that the extroverts lie more than the introverts, that men say more "self-oriented liars", while women say more "orientated towards others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less frequently to their mates than those who are not married (but the lies they usually say tend to be "normous").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty by lying to you.
How to know if someone's lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called "creating a baseline."
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the position of the subject, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It's better to know if someone usually hits with his foot all the time not to make unfair accusations when he sees his feet beating in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal and non-verbal behavioural groups.
Consider these behavioural groups as warning signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of the body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, change their position significantly, or exhibit a "post-interview shock" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of position once all the difficult questions are over.
