Valid cut "analog blackout" in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional disputes brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree advancing the so-called "analog blackout" from 2021 to 2015, by failing to meet the eight votes needed to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional dispute promoted by the Senate of the Republic was rejected for failing to reach the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and the decree remains in force.
The draft judgment, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favour of the project, only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree, and by admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions in it arranged for the digital transition.
The full House of Ministers also decided to dismiss the demand put forward by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering the discussion of the project, also by Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the President-in-Office said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the preparation of the public administration.
"I also do not consider that if it were to be done, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector corresponds to the federal executive, who is constitutionally mandated, the rectory of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years, and it translates into better use of the radio spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
To postpone the change, he said, would delay the benefits of digitisation, which involves a decision of public interest, which has not only a technical dimension, "can cover economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "requires the operation of the entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic rectory of the State, includes a group of powers which the Constitution leads to the power of the State executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the digital transition, and had done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, which in some way invades the area of competence of Congress, since compliance with the laws issued by the legislature is being provided in the administrative field, he said.
