Any blockade or delay in their efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks came under pressure to warn that a failure in Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
He'll end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief breath at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister will succeed.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.8 billion, would be too much for the current financial defences of the eurozone.
Monti has said that his government should last until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the generalized predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before the elections are made.
