MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Social Security conducts research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it conducts a research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Obesity of Children and Adolescents' protocol, which will enable them to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialities Hospital of the National Medical Center 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionologists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) from the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population to participate whether or not they are eligible, to visit IMSS's participating sports units in the Mexico Valley, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday starting at 8:00.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Quauhtémoc Sports Unit (Posient Mexico State) and that since 8 October, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (East Mexico State).
Once the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day was celebrated on 14 November, the goal was to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and family history of disease, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that Saturdays are applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (Genes are identified that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this investigation is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys noted that in just six years, there was an increase, in the case of children, of 77 per cent in obesity, and of girls of 47 per cent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed', said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country's population differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that overall, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in fat form.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows to detect whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-coloured folds (canthosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the probability of metabolic and even prediabetes changes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors deliver it in writing to the parents, who are explained to each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle they must make in order to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid bakes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent to the floor were taken care of, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand baths each season of rain in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the construction and maintenance of an asphalt floor is the right one, the bags could be reduced in quantity or, even, completely eliminated.
In his conference A technological opinion of the baches, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory in charge develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of bass.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight ones, called asphaltenes, and other low molecular weights, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and 50 degrees centigrade has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
The above means that in the streets asphalt resistance is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitute the folder, pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphaltic folder, it abounded, placed a last layer called a bearing folder, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e. a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, you must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the floor that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the bearing folder also requires the appropriate thickness and the material to be taken care of.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil is wet, the water is spread inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a rebalancing of all layers of the floor and therefore the formation of baches.
