Although Canada occupies the tenth place, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the issue of death."
With medication or not, 77 per cent of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the fact that most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying at the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this sense is recorded by Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not match the position of the Federal Government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, which have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not resulted in an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or suicide assisted by persons who are not competent or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, claimed yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"In Canada euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal."
"In Canada, assisted suicide is practiced, although it is clearly illegal," Jocelyn Downie explains.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
Let us remember that 85 per cent of Canadians have already spoken in favour of euthanasia, since they believe that it would allow people whose death is near to relieve their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of older or disabled people are less valuable.
As for those who have committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents believe that a process should not be initiated against them.
With regard to the maintenance or interruption of health care for a patient, the situation is not so clear, according to the authors of the report.
Furthermore, among its recommendations, it suggests that the Criminal Code states that the withdrawal of health care, if legally rejected, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The Committee of Experts also requests that health professionals be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient rejects assistance at the end of his life without fear of responding to a complaint.
In the area of palliative care, the Committee calls for Governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not only in cancer cases.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in the health institutions of Canada, the Committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be considered euthanasia and subject to the same procedures.
Other experts express reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations regarding the findings of the report of the experts of the Royal Society of Canada.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described as "extreme" the position of the experts who sign the report, among other things because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to the terminally ill.
"This leaves the door open to a situation in which someone who is tired of living and over 18 years of age can ask for help in committing suicide," says Deschamps, who consulted yesterday a summary of the report.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report appear to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value of society.
However, he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations".
The health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" to the findings of the report, which she called "manifest for euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, is particularly critical of the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
