Energy policy:
the facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is appropriate for an election meeting to be a time for reflection on these issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic developments will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a large part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing shortage of fossil resources must be alleviated in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to renounce nuclear energy.
That is not the case either of Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or of Switzerland, which aims only to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, for example, continue with their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, returning to the construction of a interrupted power plant following the accident of Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such speech.
The election of Berlin will lead to an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noted.
Consideration should be given to the case of Denmark.
Europe's wind champion, with 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the record of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than those of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would result in a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would leave realism to the wonderful declarations on the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
It is a price which the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not manifest opposition to that kind of energy by principle, as the surveys show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 executive jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Extensively export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and which can create non-removable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would entail the sacrifice of much of these SMEs and the loss of EUR 6 billion annually in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would charge an EPR designed to operate sixty years, when the collapse of its manufacturer is planned?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, as there is no diabolical source.
The development by Areva of low-carbon and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamenville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In the middle of the century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not cause any consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and to unforgivable human failings.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural disasters, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While all the electric actors who want to build a power plant study, the interruption of their construction in Flamenville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy implemented by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized starting from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the statistics policy, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of the "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped to the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the Libération newspaper of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely looked at economically.
The question is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people should not be a problem for a country with about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was Michel Rocard saying that France "cannot take care of all the world's misery" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish fountains.
On both sides, immigrants are regarded as a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande merely includes banality, indicating that the codecrollo will solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally profitable, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, in particular the underqualified, by pressuring them to reduce their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are actually rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and are primarily employed in sectors with a lack of employment.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country where there is a lack of anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes their arrival to have a positive impact on the wages and employment of nationals.
Taking into account the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows represents a rise in real long-term wages between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants contribute contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of American Nobel prizes naturalized and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization, for example, estimates that an immigrant in Germany who is 30 years of age will make a net contribution (less-expendited income) of EUR 150,000 to average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term of office, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go look for the points of growth he lacked "with his teeth".
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
