The world lounge of chip cards starts on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in worldwide sales of cards with microprocessors (bank cards, SIM cards phones, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to calculations by the Eurosmart office.
The most powerful segment is that of contactless technology, which allows you to pay for common transport or purchases simply by approaching a card to a reader.
This year will be sold worldwide 460 million cards with contactless chip, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share should continue to increase in 2012 (expected 580 million units) and represent about 10% of the world’s chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe, which has long been backward in relation to the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the non-contact payment sector.
About 26 million Visa bank cards already have this function, which is accepted in 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, their beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa cards are being used without contact.
But the big surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million Pass MasterCard cards this year without contact.
In order to make the top march, however, it is necessary for banks to make them available to their customers.
"There are two large French establishments that have committed themselves to spread systematically in the future, among their customers, bank cards with no contact system," says Gerard Nebouy, director general of Visa Europe France.
Banks Prove Mobile Phone Payment
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, which is essential for making transactions.
"They're retarding."
"But I should finally experience a real boom next year."
"We expect to sell between 80 and 120 million units worldwide in 2012," explains Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
The Credit Farm Bank announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and June in Caen.
The iPhones of about 200 customers and collaborators will be equipped with a cover that allows the payment without contact.
The CPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the General Society has also said yesterday that it is preparing for the marketing of an offer that allows its customers to pay without contact through their mobile.
From Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the Al Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, which had long been suspected, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers already "has the certainty".
"The way in which both organizations operate and intelligence service reports demonstrate that they are cooperating," he explained, without providing more details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the gateways.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by persons related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the following day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian researchers discovered several telephone chips belonging to terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers particularly captured the interest of the researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly wait to have more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys financial and intellectual support outside and that it is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" have become increasingly evident in the evolution and discourses of Boko Haram or in its operational modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex kamikazes or explosive devices and in the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressuring Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, take time to consider the group as a community of illuminators unworthy of interest.
QuickSuccessful
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist Imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in hausa, "Western education is a sin") encourages the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the northern Muslim region of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is living a quick success.
It is politicized and demands strict respect for sharia, while its militants engage in the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are primarily aimed at churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram's militants were particularly active and the attacks on the police stations multiplied.
Abuya's reaction was, as it usually happens, widespread.
The army attacked the city and recorded 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested in life, receives death in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern feudal lands.
Last Christmas, he claims an attack that causes 80 deaths in Jos and then another one in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, in particular against the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of these.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations became its first international objective.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would cover from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, is disturbing to all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and the Somalis of Al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram is emerging as a new threat in the centre of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was willing to share all the information.
