The North Stream, the new Russian gas entrance door in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea bottom, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a big pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned together the steering wheel of the valve that controls Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, each year 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas additional to Western Europe will arrive through a first had 1,224 km communicating the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is expected to be completed at the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, that is sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time of this huge work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, the North Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding land passage by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose some power: for them, it will be harder to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream as a "new German-Soviet covenant", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But price is a weakening of the Europe of energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to succeed in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large gas consumers and increasingly limited reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that joins us organically," said François Fillon during the opening of the gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the great contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the managers of Gazprom, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from the anchorages of the ships.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, by precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream society.
It was also necessary to extremeize the measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform in the waters of Sweden was planned, but the project leaders gave up on it, seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to establish itself permanently in the sea off their shores.
"In case of damage, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released to the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that an escape will occur, since they have planned joints that, according to the forecasts, they will have a flight every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is guaranteed by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, which conducts external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
With the shape of a pure, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full journey days at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for any kind of repair.
The flow of gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the stakes.
It was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
After that, Gazprom rented the company, for a period of 25 years renewable, all gas transport capacities.
"Gazprom will pay you for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually being transported," Jens Müller says.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been reduced by 30 per cent by the contribution of the shareholders and by 70 per cent by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7.400 million for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom assumes the risk of spending alone.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Some valves, with 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand card.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine Papers with the current appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch to the market a book of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, took care of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the soft skin skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of book was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the present taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode Mode Mode.
And he made it.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first few years has been far away, in which only 3,000 Books were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and worshiped.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers at its beginning, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city centre, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the height of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard tapas, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer wallpapers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the SG Capital Europe investment fund, currently Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled starts today.
Despite a determined public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disheartening?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made for fifteen years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"But there is still so much to be done."
It should be noted that disabled persons continue to face many obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80 per cent have not finished the Bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared with 38 per cent of the average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the main problem," says Christian Grapin, general director of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
Moreover, there are those who are not mentioned; the mentality of people advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur Association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge on low disabilities", with "excessive representation of persons in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the objective of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date back to 2008, they reach a 2.6% ratio.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishment "submitted to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, has decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The Act of 2005, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
